  <title>Bond Formation</title>
   
   <question id="chemLev_LBD02_1">
       <body>Predict what would compound would be formed when magnesium and oxygen are added to the same solution.  </body>
<multiple_choice>
    <choice value="mag_cat2_ox_anion2">Magnesium would form the cation Mg<sup>2+</sup>; oxygen would form the anion O<sup>2-</sup>; to form magnesium oxide (MgO).</choice>
    <choice value="mag_anion2_ox_cat2">Magnesium would form the anion Mg<sup>2+</sup>; oxygen would form the cation O<sup>2-</sup> , to form magnesium oxide (MgO).</choice>
    <choice value="mag_gain2_ox_loose2">Magnesium would gain 2e<sup>-</sup>; oxygen would loose 2e<sup>-</sup> to form magnesium oxide (MgO).</choice>
    <choice value="mag_loose6_ox_gain6">magnesium would loose 6 e-; oxygen would gain 6 electrons, to form magnesium oxide, (MgO).</choice>
</multiple_choice>
       <part>
           <response match="mag_cat2_ox_anion2" score="1">
               <feedback>Good Job. Magnesium with a low electronegativity will loose the 2e<sup>-</sup> to form the cation Mg<sup>2+</sup>; whereas oxygen with a high electronegativity will gain 2e<sup>-</sup> to form the anion O<sup>2-</sup>. Mg<sup>2+</sup> and O<sup>2-</sup> will react in a 1:1 ratio to cancel the charges</feedback>
           </response>
           <response match="mag_anion2_ox_cat2" score="0">
               <feedback>That is not quite right. Magnesium with low electronegativity looses e<sup>-</sup> to form a positively charged ion called a cation; oxygen with its high elctronegativity gains e<sup>-</sup> to form a negatively charged ion called an anion.</feedback>
           </response>
           <response match="mag_gain2_ox_loose2" score="0">
               <feedback>That is not quite right. Metals tend to loose electrons whereas non metals gain electrons</feedback>
           </response>
           <response match="mag_loose6_ox_gain6" score="0">
               <feedback>It is easier to loose 2e<sup>-</sup> than to gain 6e<sup>-</sup> for magnesium, and for oxygen it is easier to gain 2e<sup>-</sup> than to loose 6e<sup>-</sup>.</feedback>
           </response>
           <hint>Magnesium has 12e<sup>-</sup> with an arrangement of 2.8.2; oxygen has 6e<sup>-</sup> with an arrangement 2.6.</hint>
           <hint>Magnesium has a low electronegativity whereas oxygen has a higher electronegativity.</hint>
           <hint> Magnesium loses its e<sup>-</sup> to form a cation; oxygen gains electrons to form an anion.</hint>
       </part>
   </question>
    
    
